2020)\n| [[Philips]], [[Jewelry]], self-made\n| [[Netherlands]], but living all over the world\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Historical==\n{{see|List of banking families}}\nExcluding [[monarch|royal dynasties]] and land-owning [[aristocracy]], the wealthiest families since the emergence of [[banking]] and early [[capitalism]] in the [[Italian Renaissance]] were:{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*The [[Bardi family]] of [[Florence]] (14th century)\n*The '''Jamalullail''' family, the richest family from [[Indonesia]] \n*The [[Medici]] family, as owners of the [[Medici Bank]], the richest family in 15th-century Europe.<ref>{{citation |last=de Roover|first=Raymond Adrien |authorlink= |year=1966|title=The rise and decline of the Medici Bank: 1397\u20131494 |place=New York City; Toronto |publisher=W. W. Norton; George J. McLeod Limited (respectively) |lccn=63-11417}}</ref>\n*The [[Gondi family]] of Florence, financial partners of the Medici family in the 15th century.\n*The [[Fugger]] family of mercantile bankers and venture capitalists was among the richest families in the 16th century.<ref>Daniel Eckert,[https://www.welt.de/wirtschaft/article155974825/So-wurde-Fugger-zum-reichsten-Menschen-der-Geschichte.html So wurde Jakob Fugger zum reichsten Menschen der Historie] (\"This is how Jakob Fugger became the wealthiest person in history\"), ''[[Die Welt]]'', 6 June 2016 {{in lang|de}}. \"Auf heutige Verh\u00e4ltnisse hochgerechnet l\u00e4ge das Verm\u00f6gen des Bauernenkels bei unglaublichen 400 Milliarden Dollar (354 Milliarden Euro). In die N\u00e4he dieses Wertes kamen nur die Rothschilds, die in ihrer Glanzzeit im 19. Jahrhundert die m\u00e4chtigste Bankiersfamilie der Welt waren\" (\"Adjusted to current-day conditions, the net worth of the farmer's grandson would be close to astonishing 400 billion dollars (354 billion Euro). Only the Rothschild family, at their peak in the 19th century the most powerful family of bankers, came close to such a figure.\"</ref>\n*The [[Welser]] family, alongside the Fugger one of the most important families of merchant bankers in 16th-century Europe.\n*The [[Baring family]], owners of an important [[merchant bank]] in [[London]] in the 18th to 19th centuries.\n*The [[Schr\u00f6der family]], a leading [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic]] family of [[Hamburg]] in the 18th to 19th centuries.\n*The [[Rothschild family]] of bankers became the richest family in the mid-19th century.<ref>Niall Ferguson, ''[[The Ascent of Money]]'' (2008), p. 88: \"Between 1818 and 1852, the combined capital of the five Rothschild 'houses' (Frankfurt, London, Naples, Paris and Vienna) rose from \u00a31.8 million to \u00a39.5 million. As early as 1825 their combined capital was nine times greater than that of Baring Brothers and the Banque de France. By 1899, at \u00a341 million, it exceeded the capital of the five biggest German joint-stock banks put together.\"</ref>\n*The [[Goldman\u2013Sachs family]], owners of the [[Goldman Sachs]] investment bank from 1869 to 1912.<ref>The company admitted the first partner who was not a family member in 1912, and Henry Goldman resigned in 1917. William D. Cohan, ''Money and Power: How Goldman Sachs Came to Rule the World'' (2012).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Gauri Bhatia, [https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/27/heres-how-indias-wealthiest-families-are-seeking-to-stay-wealthy.html Here's how India's wealthiest families are seeking to stay wealthy], ''CNBC'', 18 October 2017\n*Simone Foxman, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-09/world-s-richest-families-seeking-to-make-more-deals-on-their-own World's Richest Families Seeking to Make More Deals on Their Own], ''Bloomberg'', 9 November\n* [https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/money-and-power/g12919295/richest-families/ The T&C 50: The Richest Families You've Never Heard Of], ''[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town & Country]]'', 17 October 2017,\n*Kerry A. Dolan and Luisa Kroll, [https://www.forbes.com/2001/06/21/0621dynasty.html#3c7ea3841b55 \"Billionaire Dynasties\"], ''Forbes'', 21 June 2001 \n* Devon Pendleton, Bloomberg, [https://www.registercitizen.com/news/article/Europe-s-richest-royal-gets-richer-as-family-bank-12313630.php Europe's richest royal gets richer as family bank lures wealthy], ''The Register Citizen'', 28 October 2017\n* Tom Metcalf and Jack Witzig, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-27/world-s-wealthiest-gain-1-trillion-in-17-on-market-exuberance World's Wealthiest Became $1 Trillion Richer in 2017], ''[[Bloomberg News]]'', 27 December 2017\n*Kimberley Richards, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/richest-families-canada-wealth-worth-value-rich-poor-money-a8473226.html 87 richest families in Canada have 4,000 times more wealth than average family, report says], ''Independent'', 1 August 2018\n\n{{Extreme wealth|state=expanded}}\n{{Lists of people by net worth|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Business families]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by wealth]]\n[[Category:Lists of superlatives]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\nVarious lists of '''the richest families in the world''' (excluding [[royal families]] or [[autocratic]] ruling dynasties) are published internationally, by [[Forbes]]<ref>\n{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2015/07/01/billion-dollar-bloodlines-americas-richest-families-2015/|title=Billion-Dollar Bloodlines: America's Richest Families 2015|last=Dolan|first=Kerry A.|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"CrimeRussiaList\">{{cite web | title=The richest Russian family clans \u2013 2016 | website=Crime Russia| url=https://en.crimerussia.com/oligarchs/forbes-rating-the-richest-russian-family-clans-2016/ | access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref> as well as other business magazines.\n\nThere is a distinction between wealth held by  identifiable [[The World's Billionaires|individual billionaires]] or a \"[[nuclear family]]\" and the wider notion of a historical \"[[dynasty]],\" where the wealth of a historically [[family]]-owned company or business has become distributed between various branches of descendants,<ref>\nJohn Pitman, Cristina von Zeppelin, Chandrani Ghosh, David Armstrong, [https://www.forbes.com/2002/02/28/0228dynasties.html The Dynasties], ''Forbes'', 28 February 2002. \"The names are famous and often synonymous with great brands, from spaghetti to tires; those who bear them are without question fabulously wealthy. Yet the Rothschilds, Rockefellers, Michelins and 47 other billionaire families don't appear on the Forbes World's Richest People list. Why not? It's a question of degrees. We have tried to distinguish between fortunes that belong to individuals or nuclear families, and those that have been passed down through more than one branch of the family tree and are often shared by dozens of heirs.\"</ref> usually throughout decades, ranging from several individuals to hundreds of offspring (such as the [[Rothschild family]]).<ref>Note: The Rothschild family is one of the world's richest families [https://www.valuewalk.com/2017/01/rothschilds-look-one-richest-families-world/], accumulating wealth since their rise in the 19th century, which is now divided among a web of descendants. However, the ownership structure is often opaque, which makes it hard to estimate the family wealth, and there have been controversial, often [[Antisemitic conspiracy theories|conspiratorial]] attempts to do so. Sources: [https://www.ft.com/content/f159e16a-3610-11df-aa43-00144feabdc0/ \"The Rothschilds\u2019 family fortune\"], ''[[Financial Times]]'', 25 March 2010, and [https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/rothschild-family-wealth/ \"FACT CHECK: Rothschild Family Wealth], ''[[Snopes]]''</ref> According to [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], the world's 25 richest families control $1.4 trillion (1,400,000,000,000) of wealth.<ref name=\"bloomberg2019\">{{cite web | title=The World's Wealthiest Family Gets $4 Million Richer Every Hour| website=Bloomberg | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/richest-families-in-the-world/ | access-date=11 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary rankings==\n\n{{expand list|date=February 2018}}\n\n{{selfref|Not included in the scope of this page are [[royal families]], for which see [[List of the richest royals]].}}\n\n''Note: The list includes families who, according to reliable sources, have a combined net worth of 1 billion US Dollars and above.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Family name\n! Notable members\n! data-sort-type=number |Combined wealth<br />in US$ [[1,000,000,000|billions]]<br />(estimated)\n! Source of<br />wealth\n! Country or region\n|-\n| [[Walton family|Walton]]<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web | last=Hanbury | first=Mary | title=MEET THE WALTONS: How America's wealthiest family spends its Walmart fortune | website=Business Insider | date=2018-02-24 | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/how-the-waltons-spend-their-fortune-2017-7 | access-date=2018-03-09}}</ref>\n| [[Jim Walton]], [[Alice Walton]], [[S. Robson Walton]], [[Lukas Walton]], [[Christy Walton]], [[Ann Walton Kroenke]], [[Nancy Walton Laurie]]\n| 190.5 (2019)\n| [[Wal-Mart]], [[Sam's Club]]\n| United States\n|-\n| [[Mars family|Mars]]<ref name=\"Investopedia\"/>\n| [[John Franklyn Mars]], [[Jacqueline Mars]], [[Marijke Mars]], [[Pamela Mars]], [[Valerie Mars]], [[Victoria Mars]]\n| 126.5 (2019)\n| [[Mars, Incorporated]]\n| United States \n|-\n| [[Koch family|Koch]]<ref name=\"Investopedia\"/>\n| [[Charles Koch]], [[Julia Koch]], [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill Koch]]\n| 124.5 (2019)\n| [[Koch Industries]]\n| United States\n|-\n| [[Slim family|Slim]]<ref name=\"Investopedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/articles/insights/052416/top-10-wealthiest-families-world.asp|title=Top 10 Wealthiest Families in the World|last=Ross|first=Sean|website=[[Investopedia]]|access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n| [[Ca